com.stormpath.sdk.convert

Class MapToJwtConverter

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.stormpath.sdk.convert.MapToJwtConverter
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Function<Map<String,?>,String>

    public class MapToJwtConverter
extends Object
implements Function<Map<String,?>,String>
    Converts a Map<String,?> to a compact JWT string.

    See the constructor JavaDoc for usage options.

    Instances of this class are immutable and thread-safe.

    Since:
    1.3.0

        Creates a new instance based on the specified arguments.
        baseHeader

        The optional (nullable) baseHeader argument allows you to supply any base header name/value pairs that should be in the JWT before the JWT is constructed. Any header values required by JWT construction will overwrite any identically named values in this map. For example, iat - 'issued at' will always be the timestamp when the JWT is constructed, even if baseHeader contains an iat member.

        A common reason for setting this value would be, for example, to set the identifier of the signing key used during signing (via the kid header). This allows a recipient of the JWT to look up the same signing key based on the kid header so the recipient can verify the signature.

        baseClaims

        The optional (nullable) baseClaims argument allows you to supply any base claims you wish to add as JWT claims before the function value's name/value pairs are applied as claims.

        For example, consider the following code with a baseClaims constructor argument:

        
 Map<String,Object> baseClaims = new HashMap<>();
 baseClaims.put("iss", "My Company");
 baseClaims.put("aud", "mywebapp.com");

 MapToJwtConverter converter = new MapToJwtConverter(baseClaims, null, null, null);

        If you were to invoke this converter with a Map value:

        
 Map<String,Object> value = new HashMap<>();
 value.put("username", "jsmith");
 value.put("email", "jsmith@mailinator.com");

 String jwt = converter.apply(value);

        The resulting JWT claims will be the set union of both maps and look like this:

        
     {
         "iss": "My Company",
         "aud": "webapp.com",
         "username": "jsmith",
         "email", "jsmith@mailinator.com"
     }

        Any name/value pairs in the function value take precedence and will overwrite (replace) any identically named pairs from the baseClaims.

        If you don't want the value name/value pairs to be set as common/top-level claims and instead want them to be set as a single claim with nested pairs, specify the valueClaimName argument.

        A null baseClaims argument value indicates no base claims need to be represented in the resulting JWT.

        valueClaimName

        By default, any name/value pairs in the Map value supplied to the apply method will be merged and potentially overwrite any pairs that might have been set in the baseClaims.

        If you don't want the function value's name/value pairs to be intermixed with any other JWT base claims, you can set the valueClaimName argument and that will be used to set a single top-level JWT claim using the entire Map value as the claim value.

        For example, consider the following code with a valueClaimName constructor argument:

        
 MapToJwtConverter converter = new MapToJwtConverter(null, "account", null, null, null);

        If you were to invoke this converter with a Map value:

        
 Map<String,Object> value = new HashMap<>();
 value.put("username", "jsmith");
 value.put("email", "jsmith@mailinator.com");

 String jwt = converter.apply(value);

        The resulting JWT claims will include an account claim with the same value as the function argument. The resulting JWT claims would look like this:

        
     {
         "iat": "2016-12-15T19:58:55.272Z",
         //other claims added by the JWT building process truncated for brevity...
         "account": {
             "username": "jsmith",
             "email": "jsmith@mailinator.com"
         }
     }

        The entire map value is 'nested' under a claim name equal to the specified valueClaimName argument value ("account" in this example).

        A null valueClaimName argument value indicates that any name/value pairs from the function value should not be nested, and instead be represented as common/top-level JWT claims.

        signatureAlgorithm

        The JWT signature algorithm to use when signing the JWT with the specified signingKey argument.

        A null value indicates the JWT should not be signed at all. WARNING: JWT values in most production environments should usually always be signed to ensure the JWT cannot be manipulated after construction. Not signing JWTs usually leads to security risks.

        If signatureAlgorithm is specified (non-null), the signingKey argument must be specified as well.

        signingKey

        The signing key to use when signing the JWT based on the specified signatureAlgorithm argument.

        If signatureAlgorithm is provided, the signingKey must be provided as well.

        Parameters:
        baseHeader - any base name/value pairs to add to the JWT header before constructing the JWT, or null if no base header pairs are desired.
        baseClaims - any base claims to add to the JWT before the function value is applied as JWT baseClaims, or null if no base claims are desired.
        valueClaimName - the name of the JWT claim to represent/'wrap' the function value's name/value pairs, or null if any value pairs should be added directly as common/top-level JWT claims.
        signatureAlgorithm - the signature algorithm to use when signing the key or null if the JWT should not be signed.
        signingKey - the signing key to use with the specified signatureAlgorithm or null if the JWT should not be signed.
        expirationSeconds - the number of seconds to add to the JWT's creation timestamp, the resulting value of which will be used to set the exp Date claim. A null value indicates that the exp claim will not be set.
        notBeforeSeconds - the number of seconds to add (or subtract) to the JWT's creation timestamp, the resulting value of which will be used to set the nbf Date claim. A null value indicates that the nbf claim will not be set.
